To set up a relationship among the factors under study, experts were questioned regarding, for instance, whether variable i guides variable j or vice versa. The ISM VAXO scale was used to compare variables with each other to get the responses from the experts presented below:


V= Variable i guides variable j;



A = Variable j guides variable i;



X = Variables i and j guide each other;



O= Variables i and j are not related.

A reachability matrix was obtained by substituting binary digits 0 and 1 indicating the relationship among the factors in binary form for the V, A, X and O of the SSIM according to the following rules:

                              •

The (i,j) entry V in the SSIM leads to (i,j) entry as 1 in the reachability matrix and (j,i) entry as 0;


                              •

The (i,j) entry A in the SSIM leads to (i,j) entry as 0 in the reachability matrix and (j,i) entry as 1;


                              •

The (i,j) entry X in the SSIM leads to (i,j) entry as 0 in the reachability matrix and (j,i) entry as 1;


                              •

The (i,j) entry O in the SSIM leads to (i,j) entry as 0 in the reachability matrix and (j,i) entry as also 0.

The average matrix was obtained using equation (8) after the individual expert ratings (Table 10
                        ). Further, using equations (9) and (10), maximum and minimum values were determined for the challenges. Using equations 11–13, the S, R and Q values were determined, as shown in Table 11

                        . From all the strategies, the one with the minimum Q value was ranked as the best alternative, along with satisfying two conditions, as discussed in step 7 of the VIKOR methodology. Here, strategy 3 (financing SDG target strategy) obtained the first rank, having the lowest Q value and satisfying both the conditions – that is, Q (S6) − Q (S3) ≥ 1/(7−1), and Q (S3) also obtained the top rank for R and S values, as presented in Table 12.
